{"title_page": "Lesley Fallowfield", "text_new": "{{short description|British cancer psychologist}}\n'''Professor Dame Lesley Jean Fallowfield''' [[Dame Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire|DBE]] (born October 1949)<ref name=argus>{{cite news|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/14174470.Cancer_professor_heads_list_of_Sussex_heroes_to_be_recognised_in_New_Year_s_Honours_List/|title=Cancer professor heads list of Sussex heroes to be recognised in New Year's Honours List|work=[[The Argus (Brighton)|The Argus]]|date=31 December 2015|accessdate=2 April 2016|first=Neil|last=Vowles}}</ref> is a British cancer psychologist and a professor of psycho-oncology at the [[University of Sussex]]. The main outcomes of her research have been the establishment of assessment tools to measure [[quality of life]] in clinical trials of cancer patients and the design of educational programmes to improve [[oncologist]]s' communication with their patients.\n\n==Career==\nFallowfield initially trained as a nurse at [[Guy's Hospital]] in London before studying a bachelor's degree in [[experimental psychology]] at the [[University of Sussex]] in 1980.<ref name=bmj2009>{{cite journal|title=Professor Lesley Fallowfield|journal=[[BMJ]]|year=2009|volume=339|page=b5545|doi=10.1136/bmj.b5545}}</ref><ref name=lancet>{{cite journal|journal=[[The Lancet]]|title=Lesley Fallowfield: blending psychology with science|first=Dorothy|last=Bonn|year=1999|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(05)75016-9|volume= 353|issue=9156|page=906|pmid=10093995}}</ref> She went on to complete a doctorate in [[psychophysics]] at Sussex and the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref name=shore>{{cite web|title=Professor Dame Lesley Fallowfield DBE, BSc, D.Phil, F.Med.Sci.|url=http://shore-c.sussex.ac.uk/fallowfield.htm|publisher=SHORE-C|accessdate=2 April 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415183808/http://shore-c.sussex.ac.uk/fallowfield.htm|archivedate=15 April 2016}}</ref> She had originally planned to pursue a career in visual science but the death of a friend from [[graft-versus-host disease]] secondary to a [[bone marrow transplant]] for [[acute myeloid leukaemia]] inspired her to focus on cancer.<ref name=lancet/><ref name=bmj2016>{{cite journal|title=Lesley Fallowfield: Psycho-oncology supremo|journal=[[BMJ]]|year=2016|volume=352|page=i592|doi=10.1136/bmj.i592}}</ref> In 1984, she began working for the [[King's College London]] Clinical Trials Unit,<ref name=lancet/> where she established assessment criteria to measure [[quality of life]] in trials of [[breast cancer]].<ref name=bmj2009/> These tools are in use worldwide as of 2016.<ref name=bmj2016/>\n\nFallowfield received a grant from the [[Cancer Research Campaign]] in the late 1980s to research [[oncologist]]s' communication skills and potential areas for improvement. She focused on the communications between doctors and their patients\u2014particularly in communicating complex medical concepts, giving bad news, and recruiting patients to take part in clinical trials. This led her to design educational materials to enhance doctors' communication skills and to study the resulting effects on patients' health and wellbeing.<ref name=bmj2009/> In 1990, she became the director of the Cancer Research Campaign Communication and Counselling Research Centre and a lecturer at the [[London Hospital Medical College]]. She was appointed the first professor of psycho-oncology in the United Kingdom by [[University College London]] in 1997.<ref name=lancet/>\n\nIn 2001, Fallowfield moved from UCL to the University of Sussex,<ref name=world>{{cite news|url=http://www.cancerworld.org/pdf/2298_06_13_cw11_coverstory.pdf|title=Lesley Fallowfield: getting the message across|first=Marc|last=Beishon|date=March\u2013April 2006|work=Cancer World|pages=6\u201313|accessdate=2 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104140140/http://www.cancerworld.org/pdf/2298_06_13_cw11_coverstory.pdf|archive-date=4 November 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> where she is a professor of psycho-oncology at [[Brighton and Sussex Medical School]] and the director of the University of Sussex Health Outcomes Research & Education in Cancer (SHORE-C) group.<ref name=shore/> Throughout her career she has authored over 300 articles, book chapters and textbooks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brighton.ac.uk/about-us/news-and-events/news/2016/01-08-cancer-expert-in-new-year-honours-list.aspx|title=Cancer expert recognised in New Year honours list|publisher=[[University of Brighton]]|date=8 January 2016|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nFallowfield was elected to the [[Academy of Medical Sciences, United Kingdom|Academy of Medical Sciences]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Academy of Medical Sciences]]|url=http://www.acmedsci.ac.uk/fellows/fellows-directory/ordinary-fellows/professor-lesley-fallowfield/|title=Professor Dame Lesley Fallowfield FMedSci|accessdate=2 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413015444/http://www.acmedsci.ac.uk/fellows/fellows-directory/ordinary-fellows/professor-lesley-fallowfield/|archive-date=13 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> She received the [[BMJ Group]] Lifetime Achievement Award in 2009<ref name=bmj2009/> and the Pfizer/BOA Excellence in Oncology Lifetime Achievement Award in 2010.<ref name=argus/> She was appointed a [[Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] in 2016.<ref name=argus/>\n* ESO Umberto Veronesi Memorial Award (2019)\n\n==Personal life==\nFallowfield has two children. Her son is a [[hepatologist]] and her daughter is a paediatric nurse.<ref name=bmj2016/><ref name=world/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fallowfield, Lesley}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Dames Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:British psychologists]]\n[[Category:Cancer researchers]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Sussex]]\n[[Category:Academics of University College London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Sussex]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Academy of Medical Sciences]]\n[[Category:People from Brighton]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British cancer psychologist}}\n'''Professor Dame Lesley Jean Fallowfield''' [[DBE]] (born October 1949)<ref name=argus>{{cite news|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/14174470.Cancer_professor_heads_list_of_Sussex_heroes_to_be_recognised_in_New_Year_s_Honours_List/|title=Cancer professor heads list of Sussex heroes to be recognised in New Year's Honours List|work=[[The Argus (Brighton)|The Argus]]|date=31 December 2015|accessdate=2 April 2016|first=Neil|last=Vowles}}</ref> is a British cancer psychologist and a professor of psycho-oncology at the [[University of Sussex]]. The main outcomes of her research have been the establishment of assessment tools to measure [[quality of life]] in clinical trials of cancer patients and the design of educational programmes to improve [[oncologist]]s' communication with their patients.\n\n==Career==\nFallowfield initially trained as a nurse at [[Guy's Hospital]] in London before studying a bachelor's degree in [[experimental psychology]] at the [[University of Sussex]] in 1980.<ref name=bmj2009>{{cite journal|title=Professor Lesley Fallowfield|journal=[[BMJ]]|year=2009|volume=339|page=b5545|doi=10.1136/bmj.b5545}}</ref><ref name=lancet>{{cite journal|journal=[[The Lancet]]|title=Lesley Fallowfield: blending psychology with science|first=Dorothy|last=Bonn|year=1999|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(05)75016-9|volume= 353|issue=9156|page=906|pmid=10093995}}</ref> She went on to complete a doctorate in [[psychophysics]] at Sussex and the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref name=shore>{{cite web|title=Professor Dame Lesley Fallowfield DBE, BSc, D.Phil, F.Med.Sci.|ur