ge across|first=Marc|last=Beishon|date=March\u2013April 2006|work=Cancer World|pages=6\u201313|accessdate=2 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104140140/http://www.cancerworld.org/pdf/2298_06_13_cw11_coverstory.pdf|archive-date=4 November 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> where she is a professor of psycho-oncology at [[Brighton and Sussex Medical School]] and the director of the University of Sussex Health Outcomes Research & Education in Cancer (SHORE-C) group.<ref name=shore/> Throughout her career she has authored over 300 articles, book chapters and textbooks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brighton.ac.uk/about-us/news-and-events/news/2016/01-08-cancer-expert-in-new-year-honours-list.aspx|title=Cancer expert recognised in New Year honours list|publisher=[[University of Brighton]]|date=8 January 2016|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nFallowfield was elected to the [[Academy of Medical Sciences, United Kingdom|Academy of Medical Sciences]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Academy of Medical Sciences]]|url=http://www.acmedsci.ac.uk/fellows/fellows-directory/ordinary-fellows/professor-lesley-fallowfield/|title=Professor Dame Lesley Fallowfield FMedSci|accessdate=2 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413015444/http://www.acmedsci.ac.uk/fellows/fellows-directory/ordinary-fellows/professor-lesley-fallowfield/|archive-date=13 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> She received the [[BMJ Group]] Lifetime Achievement Award in 2009<ref name=bmj2009/> and the Pfizer/BOA Excellence in Oncology Lifetime Achievement Award in 2010.<ref name=argus/> She was appointed a [[Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] in 2016.<ref name=argus/>\n* ESO Umberto Veronesi Memorial Award (2019)\n\n==Personal life==\nFallowfield has two children. Her son is a [[hepatologist]] and her daughter is a paediatric nurse.<ref name=bmj2016/><ref name=world/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fallo